# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: duckdb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] The open-source project to build Apache Parquet began as a joint effort between Twitter and Cloudera using the record shredding and assembly algorithm as described in Google's Dremel.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Parquet was designed as an improvement on the Trevni columnar storage format created by Doug Cutting, the creator of Hadoop.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] 'small compartment') refers to a style of decorative flooring and was chosen to "evoke the bottom layer of a database with an interesting layout".
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] The first version, Apache Parquet 1.0, was released in July 2013.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Since April 27, 2015, Apache Parquet has been a top-level Apache Software Foundation (ASF)-sponsored project.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the record-shredding and assembly algorithm, which accommodates the complex data structures that can be used to store data.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is implemented using the Apache Thrift framework, which increases its flexibility; it can work with a number of programming languages like C++, Java, Python, PHP, etc.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] As of August 2015, Parquet supports the big-data-processing frameworks including Apache Hive, Apache Drill, Apache Impala, Apache Crunch, Apache Pig, Cascading, Presto and Apache Spark.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] It is one of the external data formats used by the pandas Python data manipulation and analysis library.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] In Parquet, compression is performed column by column, which enables different encoding schemes to be used for text and integer data.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] This strategy also keeps the door open for newer and better encoding schemes to be implemented as they are invented.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Parquet supports various compression formats: snappy, gzip, LZO, brotli, zstd, and LZ4.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Parquet has an automatic dictionary encoding enabled dynamically for data with a *small* number of unique values (i.e. below 105) that enables significant compression and boosts processing speed.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Storage of integers is usually done with dedicated 32 or 64 bits per integer.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] For small integers, packing multiple integers into the same space makes storage more efficient.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] To optimize storage of multiple occurrences of the same value, run-length encoding is used, which is where a single value is stored once along with the number of occurrences.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Parquet implements a hybrid of bit packing and RLE, in which the encoding switches based on which produces the best compression results.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] This strategy works well for certain types of integer data and combines well with dictionary encoding.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Parquet is widely used as the underlying file format in modern cloud-based data lake architectures.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Cloud storage systems such as Amazon S3, Azure Data Lake Storage, and Google Cloud Storage commonly store data in Parquet format due to its efficient columnar representation and retrieval capabilities.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Data lakehouse frameworks—including Apache Iceberg, Delta Lake, and Apache Hudi —build an additional metadata layer on top of Parquet files to support features such as schema evolution, time-travel queries, and ACID-compliant transactions.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] In these architectures, Parquet files serve as the immutable storage layer while the table formats manage data versioning and transactional integrity.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Apache Parquet is comparable to RCFile and Optimized Row Columnar (ORC) file formats — all three fall under the category of columnar data storage within the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] They all have better compression and encoding with improved read performance at the cost of slower writes.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] In addition to these features, Apache Parquet supports limited schema evolution, i.e., the schema can be modified according to the changes in the data.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] It also provides the ability to add new columns and merge schemas that do not conflict.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] Apache Arrow is designed as an in-memory complement to on-disk columnar formats like Parquet and ORC.
[src:duckdb/apache-parquet] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing between the two formats.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:duckdb/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB was originally developed by Mark Raasveldt and Hannes Mühleisen at the Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] The project co-founders designed DuckDB to address the need for an in-process OLAP database solution.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB version 1.0.0 was released on June 3, 2024, under the codename SnowDuck.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB uses a vectorized query processing engine.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB is special amongst database management systems because it does not have any external dependencies and can be built with just a C++17 compiler.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB also deviates from the traditional client–server model by running inside a host process (it has bindings, for example, for a Python interpreter with the ability to directly place data into NumPy arrays).
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB's SQL parser is derived from the pg_query library developed by Lukas Fittl, which is itself derived from PostgreSQL's SQL parser that has been stripped down as much as possible.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB uses a single-file storage format to store data on disk, designed to support efficient scans and bulk updates, appends and deletes.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB is also compiled to WebAssembly using emscripten which enables DuckDB to run SQL in browser-based analytics tools.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB in its OLAP niche does not compete with the traditional DBMS like MSSQL, PostgreSQL and Oracle database.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] While using SQL for queries, DuckDB targets serverless applications and provides extremely fast responses using either Apache Parquet files or its own format for storage.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] These attributes make it a popular choice for large dataset analysis in interactive mode.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB is used at Facebook, Google, and Airbnb.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB co-author Mühleisen also runs a support and consultancy firm for the software, DuckLabs.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] The company has chosen not to take venture capital funding, stating "We feel investment would force the project direction towards monetization, and we would much prefer keeping DuckDB open and available for as many people as possible".
[src:duckdb/duckdb] Another company, MotherDuck, has received $100 million funding for its data platform based on DuckDB, with investors including Andreessen Horowitz.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] The company DuckLabs was formerly known as DuckDB Labs.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] The independent non-profit DuckDB Foundation safeguards the long-term maintenance and development of DuckDB.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] The foundation holds much of the intellectual property of the project and is funded by charitable donations.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] The DuckDB Foundation's statutes ensure DuckDB remains open-source under the MIT license in perpetuity.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] In addition to the native C and C++ APIs, DuckDB supports a range of programming languages.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB's architecture supports extensions, allowing additional functionality to be added dynamically.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] Many popular extensions are maintained by the core DuckDB team, and there are over 30 community extensions maintained by third parties.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] DuckDB's architecture supports dynamically loaded extensions.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] There are also over 30 community extensions maintained by third parties, covering use cases from graph queries (SQL/PGQ) to Kafka integration and ML inference.
[src:duckdb/duckdb] A full list is available at the DuckDB Community Extensions registry.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In computing, **online analytical processing (OLAP)** (/ˈoʊlæp/), is an approach to quickly answer multi-dimensional analytical (MDA) queries.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The term *OLAP* was created as a slight modification of the traditional database term online transaction processing (OLTP).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is part of the broader category of business intelligence, which also encompasses relational databases, report writing and data mining.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Typical applications of OLAP include business reporting for sales, marketing, management reporting, business process management (BPM), budgeting and forecasting, financial reporting and similar areas, with new applications emerging, such as agriculture.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP tools enable users to analyse multidimensional data interactively from multiple perspectives.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP consists of three basic analytical operations: consolidation (roll-up), drill-down, and slicing and dicing.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Consolidation involves the aggregation of data that can be accumulated and computed in one or more dimensions.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, all sales offices are rolled up to the sales department or sales division to anticipate sales trends.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] By contrast, the drill-down is a technique that allows users to navigate through the details.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] For instance, users can view the sales by individual products that make up a region's sales.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Slicing and dicing is a feature whereby users can take out (slicing) a specific set of data of the OLAP cube and view (dicing) the slices from different viewpoints.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] These viewpoints are sometimes called dimensions (such as looking at the same sales by salesperson, or by date, or by customer, or by product, or by region, etc.).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Databases configured for OLAP use a multidimensional data model, allowing for complex analytical and ad hoc queries with a rapid execution time.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] They borrow aspects of navigational databases, hierarchical databases and relational databases.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP is typically contrasted to OLTP (online transaction processing), which is generally characterized by much less complex queries, in a larger volume, to process transactions rather than for the purpose of business intelligence or reporting.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Whereas OLAP systems are mostly optimized for read, OLTP has to process all kinds of queries (read, insert, update and delete).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] At the core of any OLAP system is an OLAP cube (also called a 'multidimensional cube' or a hypercube).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] It consists of numeric facts called *measures* that are categorized by *dimensions*.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The measures are placed at the intersections of the hypercube, which is spanned by the dimensions as a vector space.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The usual interface to manipulate an OLAP cube is a matrix interface, like Pivot tables in a spreadsheet program, which performs projection operations along the dimensions, such as aggregation or averaging.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The cube metadata is typically created from a star schema or snowflake schema or fact constellation of tables in a relational database.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Measures are derived from the records in the fact table and dimensions are derived from the dimension tables.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Each *measure* can be thought of as having a set of *labels*, or meta-data associated with it.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] A *dimension* is what describes these *labels*; it provides information about the *measure*.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] A simple example would be a cube that contains a store's sales as a *measure*, and Date/Time as a *dimension*.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Each Sale has a Date/Time *label* that describes more about that sale.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is defined as "a variation of the relational model that uses multidimensional structures to organize data and express the relationships between data".
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The structure is broken into cubes and the cubes are able to store and access data within the confines of each cube.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] "Each cell within a multidimensional structure contains aggregated data related to elements along each of its dimensions".
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Even when data is manipulated it remains easy to access and continues to constitute a compact database format.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Multidimensional structure is quite popular for analytical databases that use online analytical processing (OLAP) applications.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Analytical databases use these databases because of their ability to deliver answers to complex business queries swiftly.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Data can be viewed from different angles, which gives a broader perspective of a problem unlike other models.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] It has been claimed that for complex queries OLAP cubes can produce an answer in around 0.1% of the time required for the same query on OLTP relational data.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The most important mechanism in OLAP which allows it to achieve such performance is the use of *aggregations*.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Aggregations are built from the fact table by changing the granularity on specific dimensions and aggregating up data along these dimensions, using an aggregate function (or *aggregation function*).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The number of possible aggregations is determined by every possible combination of dimension granularities.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The combination of all possible aggregations and the base data contains the answers to every query which can be answered from the data.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Because usually there are many aggregations that can be calculated, often only a predetermined number are fully calculated; the remainder are solved on demand.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The problem of deciding which aggregations (views) to calculate is known as the view selection problem.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] View selection can be constrained by the total size of the selected set of aggregations, the time to update them from changes in the base data, or both.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The objective of view selection is typically to minimize the average time to answer OLAP queries, although some studies also minimize the update time.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Many approaches to the problem have been explored, including greedy algorithms, randomized search, genetic algorithms and A* search algorithm.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Some aggregation functions can be computed for the entire OLAP cube by precomputing values for each cell, and then computing the aggregation for a roll-up of cells by aggregating these aggregates, applying a divide and conquer algorithm to the multidimensional problem to compute them efficiently.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, the overall sum of a roll-up is just the sum of the sub-sums in each cell.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Functions that can be decomposed in this way are called decomposable aggregation functions, and include `COUNT`, `MAX`, `MIN`, and `SUM`, which can be computed for each cell and then directly aggregated; these are known as self-decomposable aggregation functions.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In other cases, the aggregate function cannot be computed without analyzing the entire set at once, though in some cases approximations can be computed; examples include `DISTINCT COUNT`, `MEDIAN`, and `MODE`; for example, the median of a set is not the median of medians of subsets.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] These latter are difficult to implement efficiently in OLAP, as they require computing the aggregate function on the base data, either computing them online (slow) or precomputing them for possible rollouts (large space).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP systems have been traditionally categorized using the following taxonomy.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP (multi-dimensional online analytical processing) is the classic form of OLAP and is sometimes referred to as just OLAP.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP stores this data in an optimized multi-dimensional array storage, rather than in a relational database.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Some MOLAP tools require the pre-computation and storage of derived data, such as consolidations – the operation known as processing.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Such MOLAP tools generally utilize a pre-calculated data set referred to as a data cube.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The data cube contains all the possible answers to a given range of questions.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] As a result, they have a very fast response to queries.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] On the other hand, updating can take a long time depending on the degree of pre-computation.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Pre-computation can also lead to what is known as data explosion.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Other MOLAP tools, particularly those that implement the functional database model do not pre-compute derived data but make all calculations on demand other than those that were previously requested and stored in a cache.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Examples of commercial products that use MOLAP are Cognos Powerplay, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy, Microsoft Analysis Services, Essbase, TM1, Jedox, and icCube.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] While ROLAP uses a relational database source, generally the database must be carefully designed for ROLAP use.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] A database which was designed for OLTP will not function well as a ROLAP database.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Therefore, ROLAP still involves creating an additional copy of the data.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] However, since it is a database, a variety of technologies can be used to populate the database.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In the OLAP industry ROLAP is usually perceived as being able to scale for large data volumes but suffering from slower query performance as opposed to MOLAP.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP Survey, the largest independent survey across all major OLAP products, being conducted for 6 years (2001 to 2006) have consistently found that companies using ROLAP report slower performance than those using MOLAP even when data volumes were taken into consideration.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] However, as with any survey there are a number of subtle issues that must be taken into account when interpreting the results.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Some companies select ROLAP because they intend to re-use existing relational database tables—these tables will frequently not be optimally designed for OLAP use.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The superior flexibility of ROLAP tools allows this less-than-optimal design to work, but performance suffers.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] MOLAP tools in contrast would force the data to be re-loaded into an optimal OLAP design.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The undesirable trade-off between additional ETL cost and slow query performance has ensured that most commercial OLAP tools now use a "Hybrid OLAP" (HOLAP) approach, which allows the model designer to decide which portion of the data will be stored in MOLAP and which portion in ROLAP.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] There is no clear agreement across the industry as to what constitutes "Hybrid OLAP", except that a database will divide data between relational and specialized storage.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, for some vendors, a HOLAP database will use relational tables to hold the larger quantities of detailed data and use specialized storage for at least some aspects of the smaller quantities of more-aggregate or less-detailed data.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP addresses the shortcomings of MOLAP and ROLAP by combining the capabilities of both approaches.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] HOLAP tools can utilize both pre-calculated cubes and relational data sources.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores *aggregations* in MOLAP for fast query performance, and detailed data in ROLAP to optimize time of cube *processing*.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In this mode HOLAP stores some slice of data, usually the more recent one (i.e. sliced by Time dimension) in MOLAP for fast query performance, and older data in ROLAP.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Moreover, we can store some dices in MOLAP and others in ROLAP, leveraging the fact that in a large cuboid, there will be dense and sparse subregions.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The first product to provide HOLAP storage was Holos, but the technology also became available in other commercial products such as Microsoft Analysis Services, Oracle Database OLAP Option, MicroStrategy and SAP AG BI Accelerator.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The hybrid OLAP approach combines ROLAP and MOLAP technology, benefiting from the greater scalability of ROLAP and the faster computation of MOLAP.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] For example, a HOLAP server may store large volumes of detailed data in a relational database, while aggregations are kept in a separate MOLAP store.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Each type has certain benefits, although there is disagreement about the specifics of the benefits between providers.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Unlike relational databases, which had SQL as the standard query language, and widespread APIs such as ODBC, JDBC and OLEDB, there was no such unification in the OLAP world for a long time.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The first real standard API was OLE DB for OLAP specification from Microsoft which appeared in 1997 and introduced the MDX query language.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Several OLAP vendors – both server and client – adopted it.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In 2001 Microsoft and Hyperion announced the XML for Analysis specification, which was endorsed by most of the OLAP vendors.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Since this also used MDX as a query language, MDX became the de facto standard.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Since September-2011 LINQ can be used to query SSAS OLAP cubes from Microsoft .NET.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The first product that performed OLAP queries was *Express,* which was released in 1970 (and acquired by Oracle in 1995 from Information Resources).
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] However, the term did not appear until 1993 when it was coined by Edgar F.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Codd, who has been described as "the father of the relational database".
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Codd's paper resulted from a short consulting assignment which Codd undertook for former Arbor Software (later Hyperion Solutions, and in 2007 acquired by Oracle), as a sort of marketing coup.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The company had released its own OLAP product, *Essbase*, a year earlier.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] As a result, Codd's "twelve laws of online analytical processing" were explicit in their reference to Essbase.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] There was some ensuing controversy and when Computerworld learned that Codd was paid by Arbor, it retracted the article.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] The OLAP market experienced strong growth in the late 1990s with dozens of commercial products going into market.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] In 1998, Microsoft released its first OLAP Server – Microsoft Analysis Services, which drove wide adoption of OLAP technology and moved it into the mainstream.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] OLAP clients include many spreadsheet programs like Excel, web application, SQL, dashboard tools, etc.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Many clients support interactive data exploration where users select dimensions and measures of interest.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Some dimensions are used as filters (for slicing and dicing the data) while others are selected as the axes of a pivot table or pivot chart.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Users can also vary aggregation level (for drilling-down or rolling-up) the displayed view.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Clients can also offer a variety of graphical widgets such as sliders, geographic maps, heat maps and more which can be grouped and coordinated as dashboards.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] An extensive list of clients appears in the visualization column of the comparison of OLAP servers table.
[src:duckdb/online-analytical-processing] Below is a list of top OLAP vendors in 2006, with figures in millions of US Dollars.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] There are many database management systems (DBMS) out there.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] But there is no one-size-fits-all database system.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] All take different trade-offs to better adjust to specific use cases.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Here, we try to explain what goals DuckDB has and why and how we try to achieve those goals through technical means.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] To start with, DuckDB is a relational (table-oriented) DBMS that supports the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] SQLite is the world's most widely deployed DBMS.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Simplicity in installation, and embedded in-process operation are central to its success.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB adopted the ideas of simplicity and in-process operation – but later stepped out of the realm of in-process operations through the Quack protocol.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB has **no external dependencies**, neither for compilation nor during run-time.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] For releases, the entire source tree of DuckDB is compiled into two files, a header and an implementation file, a so-called "amalgamation".
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] This greatly simplifies deployment and integration in other build processes.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] To build DuckDB, all that is required is a working C++11 compiler (note that DuckDB v2.0 will move to C++17).
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] For DuckDB, there is no DBMS server software to install, update and maintain.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB does not run as a separate process, but completely **embedded within a host process**.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] For the analytical use cases that DuckDB targets, this has the additional advantage of **high-speed data transfer** to and from the database.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] In some cases, DuckDB can process foreign data without copying.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] For example, the DuckDB Python package can run queries directly on Pandas data without ever importing or copying any data.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Thanks to having no dependencies, DuckDB is extremely portable.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] It can be compiled for all major operating systems (Linux, macOS, Windows) and CPU architectures (x86, ARM).
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] It can be deployed from small, resource-constrained edge devices to large multi-terabyte memory servers with 100+ CPU cores.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Using DuckDB-Wasm, DuckDB can also run in web browsers and even on mobile phones.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB provides APIs for C, C++, Go, Python, R, Rust, Java, Node.js and other languages.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB provides serious data management features.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] There is extensive support for **complex queries** in SQL with a large function library, window functions, etc.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB provides **transactional guarantees** (ACID properties) through our custom, bulk-optimized Multi-Version Concurrency Control (MVCC).
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Data can be stored in DuckDB's native format, a **single-file database** or in one of the supported lakehouse formats.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB's native format supports secondary indexes to speed up queries trying to find a single table entry, while lakehouse formats, including the DuckLake format can scale up to petabytes of data.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB is deeply integrated into Python and R for efficient interactive data analysis.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB is designed to support **analytical query workloads**, also known as online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] These workloads are characterized by complex, relatively long-running queries that process significant portions of the stored dataset, for example aggregations over entire tables or joins between several large tables.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Changes to the data are expected to be rather large-scale as well, with several rows being appended, or large portions of tables being changed or added at the same time.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] To efficiently support this workload, it is critical to reduce the amount of CPU cycles that are expended per individual value.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] The state of the art in data management to achieve this are either vectorized or just-in-time query execution engines.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB uses a **columnar-vectorized query execution engine**, where queries are still interpreted, but a large batch of values (a "vector") are processed in one operation.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] This greatly reduces overhead present in traditional systems such as PostgreSQL, MySQL or SQLite which process each row sequentially.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Vectorized query execution leads to far better performance in OLAP queries.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB offers a flexible extension mechanism that allows defining new data types, functions, file formats and new SQL syntax.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] In fact, many of DuckDB's key features, such as support for the Parquet file format, JSON, time zones, and support for the HTTP(S) and S3 protocols are implemented as extensions.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] User contributions are available as community extensions.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB's development started while the main developers were public servants in the Netherlands.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] We see it as our responsibility and duty to society to make the results of our work freely available to anyone in the Netherlands or elsewhere.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] This is why DuckDB is released under the very permissive MIT License and the project's intellectual property is held by the DuckDB Foundation.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] We invite contributions from anyone provided they adhere to our Code of Conduct.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] While DuckDB was originally created by a research group, it was never intended to be a research prototype.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Instead, it was intended to become a stable and mature database system.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] To facilitate this stability, DuckDB is intensively tested using Continuous Integration.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB's test suite currently contains millions of queries, and includes queries adapted from the test suites of SQLite, PostgreSQL, and MonetDB.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Tests are repeated on a wide variety of platforms and compilers.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] Every pull request is checked against the full test setup and only merged if it passes.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] In addition to this test suite, we run various tests that stress DuckDB under heavy loads.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] We run the TPC-H and TPC-DS benchmarks, and run various tests where DuckDB is used by many clients in parallel.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] To learn about projects using DuckDB, visit the Awesome DuckDB repository.
[src:duckdb/why-duckdb] DuckDB uses some components from various open-source projects and draws inspiration from scientific publications.
